        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Frequency Setup:
We propose a frequency setup between 84.05 and 87.83 GHz with a bandwidth of 937.5 MHz in each baseband to cover as many carbon-chain transitions as possible, see Table 2. For example, the spectrum in Fig. 2 from De Beck et al. (2012) covers transitions of C2H, C4H and C6H simultaneously in the small frequency range of 87.25 to 87.50 GHz. 

Spectral resolution:
The spectral resolution is chosen to about 2 km/s to have a resolution per FWHM of at least 10 for each spectral line of typical width of 30 km/s.
 
Sensitivity:
The peak flux density is estimated by the modelled intensity of C4H by Cordiner et al. The flux of the C4H ring for the N=11-10 transition near 95 GHz is about 150 mJy/beam with a simulated beam size of 1.5 arcsec x 1.7 arcsec. The strength of the emission has an uncertainty which depends on the collisional excitation and pumping rates. The emission of the carbon-chain anions is about a factor of 10 weaker than of the parent carbon chains. The carbon-chain anions have been observed in IRC+10216, e.g.  C6H- by Cernicharo et al. (2007) with the IRAM 30m telescope and C8H and C8H- by Kawaguchi et al. (2007) and references therein with the Nobeyama 45m and Greenbank 100m telescope.
The desired sensitivity that is necessary to observe the weak emission components in the shells with a signal-to-noise ratio of 3 then is about 150/10/3 mJy = 5 mJy.

Angular resolution and source extent:
For imaging the emission we need an angular resolution of 1 arcsec to resolve the internal structure in the shells of expected 2 arcsec thickness. The shells are expected at a radius of 15 to 16 arcsec and from the models also at 29 arcsec, so the largest angular structure is about 70 arcsec. In addition, we expect an extended emission of C4H in the inner CSE. Therefore we need the additional observations of the ACA and TP array to be sensitive to the extended flux. 

Integration time:
The integration time then is 31.11 min for the 12m array including calibration and overheads and 2.07 h for the ACA and TP array. Including the additional time needed for the second 12m array configuration, the total integration time is 2.85 h.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
