    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>By studying circumstellar envelopes (CSEs) of asymptotic giant branch (AGB) stars we learn more about the chemical and physical processes of molecules and dust particles in the stellar and interstellar environment and their feedback to the interstellar medium. Observing the emission of carbon-chain molecules CnH and also their anions CnH- provides information on the dissociation of the very abundant but unobservable C2H2 to C2H and the formation of longer carbon chains and cyanopolyynes HCnN. CnH molecules are tracers of the shock- and UV-induced chemistry in CSEs and are linked to the density-enhanced shells of HCnN and dust. The modelled and observed spatial distribution of the emission peaks of C2H, C4H and C6H are inconsistent. PdBI observations show that C2H, C4H and C6H all reside in a shell of 2'' width at a radius of 16'' from the central star. Chemical models, however, predict that the longer carbon chains are found at longer radii. We propose to observe several carbon chains in the CSE of IRC+10216 with ALMA to trace the weak emission components in more detail and to probe the shell substructure. The observations will further constrain the carbon-chain chemistry.</prp:abstract>
